remediation:
nginx — add a redirect server block:
  server {
      listen 80;
      server_name example.com www.example.com;
      return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
  }

Apache — in VirtualHost *:80:
  RewriteEngine On
  RewriteRule ^(.*)$ https://%{HTTP_HOST}$1 [R=301,L]

HAProxy:
  redirect scheme https code 301 if !{ ssl_fc }

Also add HSTS once HTTPS is stable to lock in the upgrade for returning visitors.

Verify: curl -I http://<host>/ | grep Location

Replace the wildcard with an explicit allowlist of trusted origins:

nginx:
  map $http_origin $cors_origin {
      'https://app.example.com' $http_origin;
      'https://admin.example.com' $http_origin;
      default '';
  }
  add_header Access-Control-Allow-Origin $cors_origin;

Express.js (cors package):
  app.use(cors({
    origin: ['https://app.example.com', 'https://admin.example.com']
  }));

Django (django-cors-headers):
  CORS_ALLOWED_ORIGINS = ['https://app.example.com']

Never use CORS wildcard on authenticated APIs.  For truly public, read-only, unauthenticated endpoints (e.g., public CDN fonts), wildcard is acceptable.

